# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-computing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:cloud-computing/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:cloud-computing/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] Function as a Service is a subset of the serverless computing ecosystem.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] The "Grain of Sand Anti-pattern" refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] "Lambda Pinball" is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] Function as a service workloads may encounter migration obstacles due to service lock-in from tight vendor integrations.
[src:cloud-computing/function-as-a-service] Hexagonal architecture can facilitate workload portability.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] A **hypervisor**, also known as a **virtual machine monitor** (**VMM**), is a type of computer software, firmware or hardware that creates and runs virtual machines.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] A computer on which a hypervisor runs one or more virtual machines is called a *host machine* or *virtualization server*, and each virtual machine is called a *guest machine*.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The hypervisor presents the guest operating systems with a virtual operating platform and manages the execution of the guest operating systems.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Unlike an emulator, the guest executes most instructions on the native hardware.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Multiple instances of a variety of operating systems may share the virtualized hardware resources: for example, Linux, Windows, and macOS instances can all run on a single physical x86 machine.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] This contrasts with operating system-level virtualization, where all instances (usually called *containers*) must share a single kernel, though the guest operating systems can differ in user space, such as different Linux distributions with the same kernel.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The term *hypervisor* is a variant of *supervisor*, a traditional term for the kernel of an operating system: the hypervisor is the supervisor of the supervisors, with *hyper-* used as a stronger variant of *super-*.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The term dates to circa 1970; IBM coined it for software that ran OS/360 and the 7090 emulator concurrently on the 360/65 and later used it for the DIAG handler of CP-67.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] In the earlier CP/CMS (1967) system, the term *Control Program* was used instead.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Some literature, especially in microkernel contexts, makes a distinction between *hypervisor* and *virtual machine monitor* (*VMM*).
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] There, both components form the overall *virtualization stack* of a certain system.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] *Hypervisor* refers to kernel-space functionality and VMM to user-space functionality.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Specifically in these contexts, a *hypervisor* is a microkernel implementing virtualization infrastructure that must run in kernel-space for technical reasons, such as Intel VMX.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Microkernels implementing virtualization mechanisms are also referred to as *microhypervisor*.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Applying this terminology to Linux, KVM is a *hypervisor* and QEMU or Cloud Hypervisor are VMMs utilizing KVM as hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] In his 1973 thesis *Architectural Principles for Virtual Computer Systems*, Robert P.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] These hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware to control the hardware and to manage guest operating systems.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The first hypervisors, which IBM developed in the 1960s, were native hypervisors.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] These hypervisors run on a conventional operating system (OS) just as other computer programs do.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Type-2 hypervisors abstract guest operating systems from the host operating system, effectively creating an isolated system that can be interacted with by the host.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The distinction between these two types is not always clear.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] For instance, KVM and bhyve are kernel modules that effectively convert the host operating system to a type-1 hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The first hypervisors providing full virtualization were the test tool SIMMON and the one-off IBM CP-40 research system, which began production use in January 1967 and became the first version of the IBM CP/CMS operating system.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] CP-40 ran on a S/360-40 modified at the Cambridge Scientific Center to support dynamic address translation, a feature that enabled virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Prior to this time, computer hardware had only been virtualized to the extent to allow multiple user applications to run concurrently, such as in CTSS and IBM M44/44X.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] With CP-40, the hardware's *supervisor state* was virtualized as well, allowing multiple operating systems to run concurrently in separate virtual machine contexts.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Programmers soon implemented CP-40 (as CP-67) for the IBM System/360-67, the first production computer system capable of full virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] IBM shipped this machine in 1966; it included page-translation-table hardware for virtual memory and other techniques that allowed a full virtualization of all kernel tasks, including I/O and interrupt handling.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] (The "official" operating system, the ill-fated TSS/360, did not employ full virtualization.) Both CP-40 and CP-67 began production use in 1967.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] CP/CMS was available to IBM customers from 1968 to early 1970s, in source code form without support.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] CP/CMS formed part of IBM's attempt to build robust time-sharing systems for its mainframe computers.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] By running multiple operating systems concurrently, the hypervisor increased system robustness and stability: Even if one operating system crashed, the others would continue working without interruption.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Indeed, this even allowed beta or experimental versions of operating systems‍—‌or even of new hardware‍—‌to be deployed and debugged, without jeopardizing the stable main production system, and without requiring costly additional development systems.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] IBM announced its System/370 series in 1970 without the virtual memory feature needed for virtualization, but added it in the August 1972 Advanced Function announcement.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Virtualization has been featured in all successor systems, such that all modern-day IBM mainframes, including the zSeries line, retain backward compatibility with the 1960s-era IBM S/360 line.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The 1972 announcement also included VM/370, a reimplementation of CP/CMS for the S/370.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Unlike CP/CMS, IBM provided support for this version (though it was still distributed in source code form for several releases).
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] *VM* stands for *Virtual Machine*, emphasizing that all, not just some, of the hardware interfaces are virtualized.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Both VM and CP/CMS enjoyed early acceptance and rapid development by universities, corporate users, and time-sharing vendors, as well as within IBM.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Users played an active role in ongoing development, anticipating trends seen in modern open source projects.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] However, in a series of disputed and bitter battles, time-sharing lost out to batch processing through IBM political infighting, and VM remained IBM's "other" mainframe operating system for decades, losing to MVS.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] It enjoyed a resurgence of popularity and support from 2000 as the z/VM product, for example as the platform for Linux on IBM Z.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] As mentioned above, the VM control program includes a *hypervisor-call* handler that intercepts DIAG ("Diagnose", opcode x'83') instructions used within a virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] This provides fast-path non-virtualized execution of file-system access and other operations (DIAG is a model-dependent privileged instruction, not used in normal programming, and thus is not virtualized.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] It is therefore available for use as a signal to the "host" operating system).
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] When first implemented in CP/CMS release 3.1, this use of DIAG provided an operating system interface that was analogous to the System/360 Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), but that did not require altering or extending the system's virtualization of SVC.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] In 1985 IBM introduced the PR/SM hypervisor to manage logical partitions (LPAR).
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Major Unix vendors, including HP, IBM, SGI, and Sun Microsystems, have been selling virtualized hardware since before 2000.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] These have generally been large, expensive systems (in the multimillion-dollar range at the high end), although virtualization has also been available on some low- and mid-range systems, such as IBM pSeries servers, HP Superdome series machines, and Sun/Oracle SPARC T series CoolThreads servers.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] IBM provides virtualization partition technology known as logical partitioning (LPAR) on System/390, zSeries, pSeries and IBM AS/400 systems.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] For IBM's Power Systems, the POWER Hypervisor (PHYP) is a native (bare-metal) hypervisor in firmware and provides isolation between LPARs.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Processor capacity is provided to LPARs in either a dedicated fashion or on an entitlement basis where unused capacity is harvested and can be re-allocated to busy workloads.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Groups of LPARs can have their processor capacity managed as if they were in a "pool" - IBM refers to this capability as Multiple Shared-Processor Pools (MSPPs) and implements it in servers with the POWER6 processor.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] LPAR and MSPP capacity allocations can be dynamically changed.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Memory is allocated to each LPAR (at LPAR initiation or dynamically) and is address-controlled by the POWER Hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] For real-mode addressing by operating systems (AIX, Linux, IBM i), the Power processors (POWER4 onwards) have designed virtualization capabilities where a hardware address-offset is evaluated with the OS address-offset to arrive at the physical memory address.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Input/Output (I/O) adapters can be exclusively "owned" by LPARs or shared by LPARs through an appliance partition known as the Virtual I/O Server (VIOS).
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] HPE provides HP Integrity Virtual Machines (Integrity VM) to host multiple operating systems on their Itanium powered Integrity systems.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Itanium can run HP-UX, Linux, Windows and OpenVMS, and these environments are also supported as virtual servers on HP's Integrity VM platform.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] While it heavily leverages HP-UX, the Integrity VM hypervisor is really a hybrid that runs on bare-metal while guests are executing.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Running normal HP-UX applications on an Integrity VM host is heavily discouraged, because Integrity VM implements its own memory management, scheduling and I/O policies that are tuned for virtual machines and are not as effective for normal applications.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] HPE also provides more rigid partitioning of their Integrity and HP9000 systems by way of VPAR and nPar technology, the former offering shared resource partitioning and the latter offering complete I/O and processing isolation.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The flexibility of virtual server environment (VSE) has given way to its use more frequently in newer deployments.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Wind River "Carrier Grade Linux" also runs on Sun's Hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Full virtualization on SPARC processors proved straightforward: since its inception in the mid-1980s Sun deliberately kept the SPARC architecture clean of artifacts that would have impeded virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Similar trends have occurred with x86/x86-64 server platforms, where open-source projects such as Xen have led virtualization efforts.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] These include hypervisors built on Linux and Solaris kernels as well as custom kernels.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Since these technologies span from large systems down to desktops, they are described in the next section.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] x86 virtualization was introduced in the 1990s, with its emulation being included in Bochs.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Intel and AMD released their first x86 processors with hardware virtualisation in 2005 with Intel VT-x (code-named Vanderpool) and AMD-V (code-named Pacifica).
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] An alternative approach requires modifying the guest operating system to make a system call to the underlying hypervisor, rather than executing machine I/O instructions that the hypervisor simulates.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] This is called paravirtualization in Xen, a "hypercall" in Parallels Workstation, and a "DIAGNOSE code" in IBM VM.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Some microkernels, such as Mach and L4, are flexible enough to allow paravirtualization of guest operating systems.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Embedded hypervisors, targeting embedded systems and certain real-time operating system (RTOS) environments, are designed with different requirements when compared to desktop and enterprise systems, including robustness, security and real-time capabilities.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] The resource-constrained nature of multiple embedded systems, especially battery-powered mobile systems, imposes a further requirement for small memory-size and low overhead.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Finally, in contrast to the ubiquity of the x86 architecture in the PC world, the embedded world uses a wider variety of architectures and less standardized environments.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Support for virtualization requires memory protection (in the form of a memory management unit or at least a memory protection unit) and a distinction between user mode and privileged mode, which rules out most microcontrollers.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] This still leaves x86, MIPS, ARM and PowerPC as widely deployed architectures on medium- to high-end embedded systems.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] As manufacturers of embedded systems usually have the source code to their operating systems, they have less need for full virtualization in this space.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Instead, the performance advantages of paravirtualization make this usually the virtualization technology of choice.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Nevertheless, ARM and MIPS have recently added full virtualization support as an IP option and has included it in their latest high-end processors and architecture versions, such as ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore and ARMv8 EL2.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] Implementation of the concept has allegedly occurred in the SubVirt laboratory rootkit (developed jointly by Microsoft and University of Michigan researchers) as well as in the Blue Pill malware package.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] However, such assertions have been disputed by others who claim that it would be possible to detect the presence of a hypervisor-based rootkit.
[src:cloud-computing/hypervisor] In 2009, researchers from Microsoft and North Carolina State University demonstrated a hypervisor-layer anti-rootkit called Hooksafe that can provide generic protection against kernel-mode rootkits.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS-cloud providers supply resources on-demand from the large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks, VPNs).
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] To deploy their applications, users install operating-system images and the application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] Users patch and maintain the operating systems.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS services are typically billed as a utility: cost reflects the amount of resources allocated or consumed.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] Typically, IaaS involves the use of a cloud orchestration technology such as OpenStack, Apache CloudStack, or OpenNebula.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] It manages the creation of a virtual machine (VM) and decides on the hypervisor (i.e. physical host) in order to start it.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] A hypervisor runs virtual machines (VMs) as guests.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] Pools of hypervisors in the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to demand by customers.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] Hypervisors include Xen, Oracle VirtualBox, Oracle VM, KVM, VMware ESX/ESXi, or Microsoft Hyper-V.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] It also enables VM migration between hosts, allocates storage volumes, and attaches them to VMs that track usage information for billing.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] An alternative to hypervisors is Linux containers, which run in isolated partitions of a Linux kernel that runs directly on the physical hardware.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containers are isolated, secured and managed using Linux cgroups and namespaces.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containerisation offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] The global IaaS market is projected to reach a value of $411.9 billion by 2030, expanding at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 22.6% from 2023 to 2030.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] This growth is primarily driven by the adoption of cloud-based infrastructure within the Banking, Financial Services, and Insurance (BFSI) sector, which employs these technologies to enhance scalability and reduce operational costs.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to use public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:cloud-computing/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS is in use within the UK Government but the technology community within government recommends consideration of Platform as a Service (PaaS) in cases where a department may not have IaaS skills and management capacity.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Hosted applications: From the 1990s traditional application service providers (ASPs) hosted (then-existing) applications on behalf of their customers.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Depending on the limitation of the underlying application, ASPs were forced to host applications on separate machines (if multiple instances of the applications could not be executed in the same physical machine) or as separate processes.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a more mature architecture which enables a similar service with lower operational cost.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Web applications: Popular consumer-oriented web applications (such as Hotmail) developed with a single application instance serving all customers.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a natural evolution from this model, offering additional customization to groups of users within (say) the same client organization.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] In a multitenancy environment, multiple customers share the same application, running on the same operating system, on the same hardware, with the same data-storage mechanism.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] The distinction between the customers is achieved during application design, so that customers do not share or see each other's data.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] This contrasts with virtualization, where components are transformed so that each customer application appears to run on a separate virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] This is attractive because redesigning an application for multitenancy can be costly, particularly for software vendors who also continue to offer an on-premises single-tenant version of their product and would otherwise have to maintain two distinct products.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] When applications are repackaged as virtual appliances, the same appliance image can be deployed in ISV-hosted, on-premises, or trusted-third-party locations, and migrated from one deployment site to another over time.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Multitenancy allows for cost savings over and above the basic economies of scale achievable from consolidating IT resources into a single operation.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] An application instance usually incurs a certain amount of memory and processing overhead which can be substantial when multiplied by many customers, especially if the customers are small.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Multitenancy reduces this overhead by spreading it over many customers.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Further cost savings may come from licensing costs of the underlying software (such as operating systems and database management systems).
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Put crudely, if you can run everything on a single software instance, you only have to buy one software license.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] In addition, development of multitenant systems is more complex, and security testing is more stringent because multiple customers' data is being commingled.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Because of the additional customization complexity and the need to maintain per-tenant metadata, multitenant applications require a larger development effort.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Considerations such as how tenant data is partitioned, how per-tenant schema extensions are stored, and how shared resources are isolated must be taken into account.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Multitenancy simplifies the release management process.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] In a traditional release management process, packages containing code and database changes are distributed to client desktop and/or server machines; in the single-instance case, this would be one server machine per customer.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] These packages then have to be installed on each individual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] With the multitenant model, the package typically only needs to be installed on a single server.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] This greatly simplifies the release management process, and the scale is no longer dependent on the number of customers.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] At the same time, multitenancy increases the risks and impacts inherent in applying a new release version.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] As there is a single software instance serving multiple tenants, an update on this instance may cause downtime for all tenants even if the update is requested and useful for only one tenant.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Also, some bugs and issues resulted from applying the new release could manifest in other tenants' personalized view of the application.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Because of possible downtime, the moment of applying the release may be restricted depending on time usage schedule of more than one tenant.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] A central design decision in a multitenant application is how each tenant's data is isolated within shared storage.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] When tenants share compute, storage, or network resources, a single tenant generating disproportionate load can degrade performance for others, a condition known as the "noisy neighbor" problem.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Mitigations include per-tenant rate limiting, resource quotas, and isolating high-demand tenants onto dedicated resources.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] According to Marc Brooker, in a multi tenant architecture, unrelated and uncorrelated workloads should be grouped together.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] That's because mixing different workloads, with different needs and patterns, hide the patterns of each workload.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Grouping workloads reduces the peak-to-average ratio of the overall system; individual workloads can utilize more resources during peak times without significantly increasing the overall cost structure of the system and subsequently helps you to achieve more cost efficiency.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Note that multiple workloads from the same application, customer or industry, tend to behave as a single workload.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are typically required to provide a high degree of customization to support each target organization's needs.
[src:cloud-computing/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are expected to provide adequate security, robustness and performance between multiple tenants which is provided by the layers below the application in case of multi-instance applications.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:cloud-computing/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:cloud-computing/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS products typically run on rented infrastructure as a service (IaaS) or platform as a service (PaaS) systems including hardware and sometimes operating systems and middleware, to accommodate rapid increases in usage while providing instant and continuous availability to customers.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS customers have the abstraction of limitless computing resources, while economy of scale drives down the cost.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS architectures are typically multi-tenant; usually they share resources between clients for efficiency, but sometimes they offer a siloed environment for an additional fee.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Common SaaS revenue models include freemium, subscription, and usage-based fees.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Unlike traditional software, it is rarely possible to buy a perpetual license for a certain version of the software.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] There are no specific software development practices that distinguish SaaS from other application development, although there is often a focus on frequent testing and releases.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) is the most basic form of cloud computing, where infrastructure resources—such as physical computers—are not owned by the user but instead leased from a cloud provider.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] As a result, infrastructure resources can be increased rapidly, instead of waiting weeks for computers to ship and set up.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] IaaS requires time and expertise to make use of the infrastructure in the form of operating systems and applications.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Platform as a service (PaaS) includes the operating system and middleware, but not the applications.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS providers typically use PaaS or IaaS services to run their applications.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Without IaaS, it would be extremely difficult to make an SaaS product scalable for a variable number of users while providing the instant and continual availability that customers expect.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Most end users consume only the SaaS product and do not have to worry about the technical complexity of the physical hardware and operating system.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Because cloud resources can be accessed without any human interactions, SaaS customers are provided with the abstraction of limitless computing resources, while economy of scale drives down the cost.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Another key feature of cloud computing is that software updates can be rolled out and made available to all customers nearly instantaneously.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] In 2019, SaaS was estimated to make up the plurality, 43 percent, of the cloud computing market while IaaS and PaaS combined account for approximately 25 percent.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] In the 1960s, multitasking was invented, enabling mainframe computers to serve multiple users simultaneously.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Over the next decade, timesharing became the main business model for computing, and cluster computing enabled multiple computers to work together.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Cloud computing emerged in the late 1990s with companies like Amazon (1994), Salesforce (1999), and Concur (1993) offering Internet-based applications on a pay-per-use basis.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] All of these focused on a single product to seize a high market share.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Beginning with Gmail in 2004, email services were some of the first SaaS products to be mass-marketed to consumers.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The market for SaaS grew rapidly throughout the early twenty-first century.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Initially viewed as a technological innovation, SaaS has come to be perceived more as a business model.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] By 2023, SaaS had become the primary method that companies deliver applications.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Popular consumer SaaS products include all social media websites, email services like Gmail and its associated Google Docs Editors, Zoom, Dropbox, and entertainment products like Netflix and Spotify.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Enterprise SaaS products include Salesforce's customer relationship management (CRM) software, SAP Cloud Platform, and Oracle Cloud Enterprise Resource Planning.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Some SaaS providers offer free services to consumers that are funded by means such as advertising, affiliate marketing, or selling consumer data.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] One of the most popular models for Internet start-ups and mobile apps is freemium, where the company charges for continued use or a higher level of service.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Even if the user never upgrades to the paid version, it helps the company capture a higher market share and displace customers from a rival.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] However, the company's hosting cost increases with the number of users, regardless of whether it is successful at enticing them to use the paid version.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Another common model is where the free version only provides demonstration (crippleware).
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Online marketplaces may charge a fee on transactions to cover the SaaS provider costs.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] It used to be more common for SaaS products to be offered for a one-time cost, but this model is declining in popularity.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] A few SaaS products have open source code, called open SaaS.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] This model can provide advantages such as reduced deployment cost, less vendor commitment, and more portable applications.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The most common SaaS revenue models involve subscription and pay for usage.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] For customers, the potential advantages include reduced upfront cost, increased flexibility, and lower overall cost compared to traditional software with perpetual software licenses.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] In some cases, the steep one-time cost demanded by sellers of traditional software were out of the reach of smaller businesses, but pay-per-use SaaS models make the software affordable.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Usage may be charged based on the number of users, transactions, amount of storage spaced used, or other metrics.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Many buyers prefer pay-per-usage because they believe that they are relatively light users of the software, and the seller benefits by reaching occasional users who would otherwise not buy the software.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] However, there are also many buyers who prefer perpetual licenses for reasons such as, high subscription prices, and subscription fatigue.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] It can also cause revenue uncertainty for the seller and increases the overhead for billing.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The subscription model of SaaS offers a continuing and renewable revenue stream to the provider, although vulnerable to cancellation.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] If a significant number are cancelled, the viability of the business can be placed in jeopardy.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The ease of canceling a subscription and switching to a competitor leave customers with the leverage to get concessions from the seller.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] While recurring revenues can help the business and attract investors, the need for customer service skills in convincing the customer to renew their subscription is a challenge for providers switching to subscription from other revenue models.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The Rule of 40 is a commonly used metric by investors to evaluate SaaS company performance, calculated as the sum of revenue growth rate and EBITDA margin (with a target combined score of 40% or above).
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS products are typically accessed via a web browser as a publicly available web application.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] This means that customers can access the application anywhere from any device without needing to install or update it.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS providers often try to minimize the difficulty of signing up for the product.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Many capitalize on the service-oriented structure to respond to customer feedback and evolve their product quickly to meet demands.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] This can enable customers to believe in the continued improvement of the product and help the SaaS provider get customers from an established traditional software company that likely can offer a deeper feature set.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Although on-premises software is often less secure than SaaS alternatives, security and privacy are among the main reasons cited by companies that do not adopt SaaS products.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS companies have to protect their publicly available offerings from abuse, including denial-of-service attacks and hacking.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] They often use technologies such as access control, authentication, and encryption to protect data confidentiality.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Nevertheless, not all companies trust SaaS providers to keep sensitive data secured.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The vendor is responsible for software updates, including security patches, and for protecting the customers' data.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS systems inherently have a greater latency than software run on-premises due to the time for network packets to be delivered to the cloud facility.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] This can be prohibitive for some uses, such as time-sensitive industrial processes or warehousing.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The rise of SaaS products is one factor that has led many companies to shift IT budgets from capital expenditure to operating expenditure.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The process of migration to SaaS and supporting it can also be a significant cost that must be accounted for.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] A challenge for SaaS providers is that demand is not known in advance.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Their system must have enough slack to be able to handle all users without turning any away, but without paying for too many resources that will be unnecessary.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] If resources are static, they are guaranteed to be wasted during non-peak time.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Sometimes cheaper off-peak rates are offered to balance the load and reduce waste.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The expectation for continuous service is so high that outages in SaaS software are often reported in the news.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] There are no specific software development practices that differentiate SaaS from other types of application development.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS products are often released early and often to take advantage of the flexibility of the SaaS delivery model.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Agile software development is commonly used to support this release schedule.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Many SaaS developers use test-driven development, or otherwise emphasize frequent software testing, because of the need to ensure availability of their service and rapid deployment.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Domain-driven design, in which business goals drive development, is popular because SaaS products must sell themselves to the customer by being useful.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS developers do not know in advance which devices customers will try to access the product from—such as a desktop computer, tablet, or smartphone—and supporting a wide range of devices is often an important concern for the front-end development team.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Progressive web applications allow some functionality to be available even if the device is offline.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS applications predominantly offer integration protocols and application programming interfaces (APIs) that operate over a wide area network.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS architecture varies significantly from product to product.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Nevertheless, most SaaS providers offer a multi-tenant architecture.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] With this model, a single version of the application, with a single configuration (hardware, network, operating system), is used for all customers ("tenants").
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] This means that the company does not need to support multiple versions and configurations.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The architectural shift from each customer running their own version of the software on their own hardware affects many aspects of the application's design and security features.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] In a multi-tenant architecture, many resources can be used by different tenants or shared between multiple tenants.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The structure of a typical SaaS application can be separated into application and control planes.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS products differ in how these planes are separated, which might be closely integrated or loosely coupled in an event- or message-driven model.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The control plane is in charge of directing the system and covers functionality such as tenant onboarding, billing, and metrics, as well as the system used by the SaaS provider to configure, manage, and operate the service.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Many SaaS products are offered at different levels of service for different prices, called tiering.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] This can also affect the architecture for both planes, although it is commonly placed in the control plane.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Unlike the application plane, the services in the control plane are not designed for multitenancy.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The application plane—which varies a great deal depending on the nature of the product—implements the core functionality of the SaaS product.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Key design issues include separating different tenants so they cannot view or change other tenants' data or resources.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Except for the simplest SaaS applications, some microservices and other resources are allocated on a per-tenant basis, rather than shared between all tenants.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Routing functionality is necessary to direct tenant requests to the appropriate services.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Some SaaS products do not share any resources between tenants—called siloing.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Although this negates many of the efficiency benefits of SaaS, it makes it easier to migrate legacy software to SaaS and is sometimes offered as a premium offering at a higher price.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Pooling all resources might make it possible to achieve higher efficiency, but an outage affects all customers so availability must be prioritized to a greater extent.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Many systems use a combination of both approaches, pooling some resources and siloing others.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Other companies group multiple tenants into pods and share resources between them.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] SaaS architecture typically allows users to access applications through a web browser without installing software on their local devices.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] This approach simplifies software maintenance and updates, as service providers can manage the application centrally.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] It also enables organizations to scale services easily according to their needs.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] In the United States, constitutional search warrant laws do not protect all forms of dynamically stored SaaS data.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] The result is that governments may be able to request data from SaaS providers without the owner's consent.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] Certain open-source licenses such as GPL-2.0 do not explicitly grant rights permitting distribution as a SaaS product in Germany.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] In 2026, with the emergence of generative AI tools, multiple SaaS companies saw a steep fall in stock market price.
[src:cloud-computing/software-as-a-service] February 3 saw a US $300 billion loss of value, in a crisis coined the "SaaS-Pocolypse".
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:cloud-computing/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] In computing, **virtualization** (or **virtualisation** in Commonwealth English; see spelling differences,) abbreviated as **v12n**, is a series of technologies that allows dividing of physical computing resources into a series of virtual machines, operating systems, processes or containers.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Virtualization began in the 1960s with IBM CP/CMS.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The control program CP provided each user with a simulated stand-alone System/360 computer.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] In hardware virtualization, the *host machine* is the machine that is used by the virtualization and the *guest machine* is the virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The words *host* and *guest* are used to distinguish the software that runs on the physical machine from the software that runs on the virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The software or firmware that creates a virtual machine on the host hardware is called a *hypervisor* or *virtual machine monitor*.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hardware virtualization is not the same as hardware emulation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Desktop virtualization is the concept of separating the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Operating system-level virtualization, also known as containerization, refers to an operating system feature in which the kernel allows the existence of multiple isolated user-space instances.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The usual goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] A form of virtualization was first demonstrated with IBM's CP-40 research system in 1967, then distributed via open source in CP/CMS in 1967–1972, and re-implemented in IBM's VM family from 1972 to the present.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Each CP/CMS user was provided a simulated, stand-alone computer.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Each such virtual machine had the complete capabilities of the underlying machine, and (for its user) the virtual machine was indistinguishable from a private system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] This simulation was comprehensive, and was based on the *Principles of Operation* manual for the hardware.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] It thus included such elements as an instruction set, main memory, interrupts, exceptions, and device access.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The result was a single machine that could be multiplexed among many users.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization first appeared on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] IBM added virtual memory hardware to the System/370 series in 1972 which is not the same as Intel VT-x Rings providing a higher privilege level for Hypervisor to properly control Virtual Machines requiring full access to Supervisor and Program or User modes.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] With the increasing demand for high-definition computer graphics (e.g.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] CAD), virtualization of mainframes lost some attention in the late 1970s, when the upcoming minicomputers fostered resource allocation through distributed computing, encompassing the commoditization of microcomputers.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The increase in compute capacity per x86 server (and in particular the substantial increase in modern networks' bandwidths) rekindled interest in data-center based computing which is based on virtualization techniques.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The primary driver was the potential for server consolidation: virtualization allowed a single server to cost-efficiently consolidate compute power on multiple underutilized dedicated servers.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The most visible hallmark of a return to the roots of computing is cloud computing, which is a synonym for data center based computing (or mainframe-like computing) through high bandwidth networks.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] It is closely connected to virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] This made it difficult to implement a virtual machine monitor for this type of processor.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Specific limitations included the inability to trap on some privileged instructions.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Therefore, to compensate for these architectural limitations, designers accomplished virtualization of the x86 architecture through two methods: **full virtualization** or **paravirtualization**.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Both create the illusion of physical hardware to achieve the goal of operating system independence from the hardware but present some trade-offs in performance and complexity.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Full virtualization was not fully available on the x86 platform prior to 2005.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Many platform hypervisors for the x86 platform came very close and claimed full virtualization (such as Adeos, Mac-on-Linux, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Parallels Workstation, VMware Workstation, VMware Server (formerly GSX Server), VirtualBox, Win4BSD, and Win4Lin Pro).
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD (working independently) created new processor extensions to the x86 architecture called Intel VT-x and AMD-V, respectively.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] On the Itanium architecture, hardware-assisted virtualization is known as VT-i.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Software executed on these virtual machines is separated from the underlying hardware resources.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] For example, a computer that is running Arch Linux may host a virtual machine that looks like a computer with the Microsoft Windows operating system; Windows-based software can be run on the virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Full virtualization employs techniques that pools physical computer resources into one or more instances; each running a virtual environment where any software or operating system capable of execution on the raw hardware can be run in the virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Two common full virtualization techniques are typically used: (a) binary translation and (b) hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Binary translation automatically modifies the software on-the-fly to replace instructions that "pierce the virtual machine" with a different, virtual machine safe sequence of instructions.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization allows guest operating systems to be run in isolation with virtually no modification to the (guest) operating system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Some hypervisors perform binary translation between guest and host, either between differing instruction set architectures or between a guest and host using the same instruction set.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The hypervisor may be designed to interpret a guest's machine code directly or generate machine code for the host's architecture in a form of dynamic binary translation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Most common hypervisors, including ones that use hardware to assist virtualization, perform binary translation of some instructions relating to hardware access.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] In such a case, the hypervisor will trap the instruction and perform the functions to emulate the required devices.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hypervisors that perform binary translation may also be designed to substitute instructions within the guest context to aid security or performance.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization (or *accelerated virtualization; Xen calls it hardware virtual machine (HVM), and Virtual Iron calls it native virtualization)* is a way of improving overall efficiency of hardware virtualization using help from the host processors.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] A full virtualization is used to emulate a complete hardware environment, or virtual machine, in which an unmodified guest operating system (using the same instruction set as the host machine) effectively executes in complete isolation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM 308X processors in 1980, with the Start Interpretive Execution (SIE) instruction.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] It was added to x86 processors (Intel VT-x, AMD-V or VIA VT) in 2005, 2006 and 2010 respectively.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] IBM offers hardware virtualization for its IBM Power Systems hardware for AIX, Linux and IBM i, and for its IBM Z mainframes.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] IBM refers to its specific form of hardware virtualization as "logical partition", or more commonly as LPAR.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization reduces the maintenance overhead of binary translation based virtualization as it reduces (ideally, eliminates) the code that needs to be translated in the guest operating system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] It is also considerably easier to obtain better performance.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Paravirtualization is a virtualization technique that presents a software interface to the virtual machines which is similar, yet not identical, to the underlying hardware–software interface.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Paravirtualization improves performance and efficiency, compared to full virtualization, by having the guest operating system communicate with the hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] By allowing the guest operating system to indicate its intent to the hypervisor, each can cooperate to obtain better performance when running in a virtual machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The intent of the modified interface is to reduce the portion of the guest's execution time spent performing operations which are substantially more difficult to run in a virtual environment compared to a non-virtualized environment.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The paravirtualization provides specially defined 'hooks' to allow the guest(s) and host to request and acknowledge these tasks, which would otherwise be executed in the virtual domain (where execution performance is worse).
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] A successful paravirtualized platform may allow the virtual machine monitor (VMM) to be simpler (by relocating execution of critical tasks from the virtual domain to the host domain), and/or reduce the overall performance degradation of machine execution inside the virtual guest.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Paravirtualization requires the guest operating system to be explicitly ported for the para-API – a conventional OS distribution that is not paravirtualization-aware can still run on a paravirtualizing VMM.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] However, even in cases where the operating system cannot be modified, components may be available that enable many of the significant performance advantages of paravirtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] For example, the Xen Windows GPLPV project provides a kit of paravirtualization-aware device drivers, that are intended to be installed into a Microsoft Windows virtual guest running on the Xen hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Such applications tend to be accessible through the paravirtual machine interface environment.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] This ensures run-mode compatibility across multiple encryption algorithm models, allowing seamless integration within the paravirtual framework.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The term "paravirtualization" was first used in the research literature in association with the Denali Virtual Machine Manager.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The term is also used to describe the Xen, L4, TRANGO, VMware, Wind River and XtratuM hypervisors.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] All these projects use or can use paravirtualization techniques to support high performance virtual machines on x86 hardware by implementing a virtual machine that does not implement the hard-to-virtualize parts of the actual x86 instruction set.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] In 2005, VMware proposed a paravirtualization interface, the Virtual Machine Interface (VMI), as a communication mechanism between the guest operating system and the hypervisor.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] This interface enabled transparent paravirtualization in which a single binary version of the operating system can run either on native hardware or on a hypervisor in paravirtualized mode.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The first appearance of paravirtualization support in Linux occurred with the merge of the ppc64 port in 2002, which supported running Linux as a paravirtualized guest on IBM pSeries (RS/6000) and iSeries (AS/400) hardware.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] At the USENIX conference in 2006 in Boston, Massachusetts, a number of Linux development vendors (including IBM, VMware, Xen, and Red Hat) collaborated on an alternative form of paravirtualization, initially developed by the Xen group, called "paravirt-ops".
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The paravirt-ops code (often shortened to pv-ops) was included in the mainline Linux kernel as of the 2.6.23 version, and provides a hypervisor-agnostic interface between the hypervisor and guest kernels.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Distribution support for pv-ops guest kernels appeared starting with Ubuntu 7.04 and RedHat 9.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Xen hypervisors based on any 2.6.24 or later kernel support pv-ops guests, as does VMware's Workstation product beginning with version 6.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Hybrid virtualization combines full virtualization techniques with paravirtualized drivers to overcome limitations with hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] A hardware-assisted full virtualization approach uses an unmodified guest operating system that involves many VM traps producing high CPU overheads limiting scalability and the efficiency of server consolidation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] The hybrid virtualization approach overcomes this problem.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Desktop virtualization separates the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] One form of desktop virtualization, virtual desktop infrastructure (VDI), can be thought of as a more advanced form of hardware virtualization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Rather than interacting with a host computer directly via a keyboard, mouse, and monitor, the user interacts with the host computer using another desktop computer or a mobile device by means of a network connection, such as a LAN, Wireless LAN or even the Internet.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] In addition, the host computer in this scenario becomes a server computer capable of hosting multiple virtual machines at the same time for multiple users.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Companies like HP and IBM provide a hybrid VDI model with a range of virtualization software and delivery models to improve upon the limitations of distributed client computing.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Selected client environments move workloads from PCs and other devices to data center servers, creating well-managed virtual clients, with applications and client operating environments hosted on servers and storage in the data center.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] For users, this means they can access their desktop from any location, without being tied to a single client device.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Since the resources are centralized, users moving between work locations can still access the same client environment with their applications and data.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] For IT administrators, this means a more centralized, efficient client environment that is easier to maintain and able to more quickly respond to the changing needs of the user and business.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Another form, session virtualization, allows multiple users to connect and log into a shared but powerful computer over the network and use it simultaneously.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Each is given a desktop and a personal folder in which they store their files.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] With multiseat configuration, session virtualization can be accomplished using a single PC with multiple monitors, keyboards, and mice connected.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Thin clients, which are seen in desktop virtualization, are simple and/or cheap computers that are primarily designed to connect to the network.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] They may lack significant hard disk storage space, RAM or even processing power, but many organizations are beginning to look at the cost benefits of eliminating "thick client" desktops that are packed with software (and require software licensing fees) and making more strategic investments.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Desktop virtualization simplifies software versioning and patch management, where the new image is simply updated on the server, and the desktop gets the updated version when it reboots.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] It also enables centralized control over what applications the user is allowed to have access to on the workstation.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Moving virtualized desktops into the cloud creates hosted virtual desktops (HVDs), in which the desktop images are centrally managed and maintained by a specialist hosting firm.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Benefits include scalability and the reduction of capital expenditure, which is replaced by a monthly operational cost.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Such instances, called containers, partitions, virtual environments (VEs) or jails (FreeBSD jail or chroot jail), may look like (physical) computers from the point of view of programs running in them.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] A computer program running on an ordinary operating system can see all resources (connected devices, files and folders, network shares, CPU power, quantifiable hardware capabilities) of that computer.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] However, programs running inside a container can only see the container's contents and devices assigned to the container.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] This provides many of the benefits that virtual machines have such as standardization and scalability, while using less resources as the kernel is shared between containers.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Containerization started gaining prominence in 2014, with the introduction of Docker.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] A common goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] With virtualization, several operating systems can be run in parallel on a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] This parallelism tends to reduce overhead costs and differs from multitasking, which involves running several programs on the same OS.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Using virtualization, an enterprise can better manage updates and rapid changes to the operating system and applications without disrupting the user.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Ultimately, virtualization dramatically improves the efficiency and availability of resources and applications in an organization.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Instead of relying on the old model of "one server, one application" that leads to underutilized resources, virtual resources are dynamically applied to meet business needs without any excess fat".
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] Virtual machines running proprietary operating systems require licensing, regardless of the host machine's operating system.
[src:cloud-computing/virtualization] For example, installing Microsoft Windows into a VM guest requires its licensing requirements to be satisfied.
